In your `App.xaml.cs`, override `CreateWindow` and subscribe to the lifecycle events on the returned `Window`:

```csharp
public partial class App : Application
{
    public App()
    {
        InitializeComponent();
    }

    protected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)
    {
        var window = new Window(new AppShell());

        window.Created   += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine("🪟 Created");
        window.Activated  += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine("🪟 Activated");
        window.Deactivated += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine("🪟 Deactivated");
        window.Stopped    += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine("🪟 Stopped");
        window.Resumed    += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine("🪟 Resumed");
        window.Destroying += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine("🪟 Destroying");

        // Visibility (desktop platforms)
        window.Backgrounding += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine("🪟 Backgrounding");

        return window;
    }
}
```

**Lifecycle order:**

| Transition | Events fired |
|---|---|
| App launch | `Created → Activated` |
| User switches away | `Deactivated → Stopped` |
| User returns | `Resumed → Activated` |
| App closed | `Destroying` |

> **Tip:** `Backgrounding` fires on iOS/macOS when the app moves to the background — use it to save transient state. On Android, `Stopped` serves the same purpose.
